UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2268
1 AN ACT relating to student rights.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 SECTION 1. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 158 IS CREATED TO
4 READ AS FOLLOWS:
5 (1) As used in this section:
6 (a) "Academic study of religion" means the objective, educational examination
7 of religious traditions, texts, history, or practices for secular scholarly
8 purposes, conducted in a manner that neither promotes nor denigrates any
9 particular religious belief or nonbelief;
10 (b) "Club" means a noncurricular student group recognized by the school
11 district and that qualifies through the safe haven provisions of 20 U.S.C sec.
12 4071(c) for protection under the Equal Access Act;
13 (c) "Coerce" means exerting direct or indirect pressure through official policy,
14 practice, or conduct, which would compel a reasonable student to
15 participate in or refrain from religious exercise against the student's
16 conscience;
17 (d) "Endorsement" means a governmental practice that a reasonable observer
18 would view as government approval, favor, or disapproval of religion or
19 particular religious beliefs;
20 (e) "Nonparticipatory capacity" means presence at a student religious club
21 meeting or event solely for supervisory purposes, as defined in the Equal
22 Access Act, without lecturing, proselytizing, praying, preaching, planning
23 religious events, or otherwise engaging in religious activities;
24 (f) "Official capacity" means when a person is:
25 1. Performing official duties or furthering the work of a school district;
26 or
27 2. Acting under or with power or authority granted by virtue of
Page 1 of 10
XXXX 2/23/2026 12:50 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2268
1 employment by or association with a school district;
2 (g) "Prayer" means a communication, either spoken or written, directed toward
3 a deity, deities, or other supernatural or spiritual force, including but not
4 limited to a benediction, invocation, chant, or request for guidance,
5 blessing, forgiveness, or intervention;
6 (h) "Proselytizing" means attempting to convert individuals from one religion,
7 religious belief, or nonbelief to another through persuasion or inducement;
8 (i) "Religious activity" means any practice, observance, or expression intended
9 primarily for religious purposes, including but not limited to prayer,
10 worship, religious instruction, or proselytizing;
11 (j) "Religious display" means any visual presentation of religious symbols,
12 texts, imagery, or artifacts that conveys a religious message or promotes
13 religious beliefs;
14 (k) "Religious text" means writing that is used primarily for devotional,
15 worship, or proselytizing purposes rather than for legitimate academic study
16 of religion, religious history, or comparative religion;
17 (l) "School event":
18 1. Means any activity at a school facility or sponsored, conducted, or
19 supervised by a school official acting in his or her official capacity;
20 2. Includes but is not limited to any graduation, grade-promotion
21 ceremony, award program, induction ceremony, pep rally,
22 competition, practice, performance, class instructional time, and club
23 meeting or event; and
24 3. Does not mean:
25 a. A student religious club meeting or event, if all school officials
26 who are present at the meeting or event are attending in a
27 nonparticipatory capacity;
Page 2 of 10
XXXX 2/23/2026 12:50 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2268
1 b. An activity at a school facility, if it is outside the presence of
2 students and no school official acts in official capacity; or
3 c. An activity at a school facility that is used by a third party
4 pursuant to a standard facility use agreement or advance written
5 permission that indicates the responsible third-party user, use
6 period, facility to be used, purpose of use, and conditions of use,
7 provided such use occurs during the agreed period, is on terms
8 consistent with other third-party users, involves no school
9 official acting in official capacity, and does not take place during
10 school hours;
11 (m) "School official" means any employee, agent, or representative of a public
12 school or school district, including but not limited to teachers,
13 administrators, coaches, and support staff;
14 (n) "School property" means any building, facility, grounds, or vehicle owned,
15 leased, or controlled by a public school or school district; and
16 (o) "Secular purpose" means an objective that is not primarily religious in
17 nature and serves a legitimate educational, administrative, or civic function.
18 (2) Notwithstanding any other statute to the contrary, all public school students shall
19 enjoy:
20 (a) The right to practice any religion they choose on school grounds or at
21 school events, provided that their practices are orderly and do not inhibit the
22 operations or safety of the school or infringe on the rights of others;
23 (b) The right to not practice any religion whatsoever, if they so choose, on
24 school property or at school events;
25 (c) The right to be free from discrimination based on their religious beliefs or
26 lack thereof;
27 (d) The right to be free from school-sponsored religious teachings or practices
Page 3 of 10
XXXX 2/23/2026 12:50 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2268
1 of all kinds on school property or at school events, including but not limited
2 to:
3 1. School official-led prayer;
4 2. Prayer led by students or adults who are not school officials, when it
5 is:
6 a. Sponsored by the school; or
7 b. Supported by the school by means of marketing, planning,
8 audio-visual equipment, or endorsement by any school official or
9 the school itself;
10 3. Any religious instruction as part of a school curriculum, including
11 creationism and intelligent design; and
12 4. Required or coerced reading of religious texts other than for the
13 academic study of religion. Any academic study of religion that
14 includes instruction of religious perspectives shall include multiple
15 religious perspectives;
16 (e) The right to be free of school-sponsored religious displays on school
17 property or at school events:
18 1. Including but not limited to:
19 a. The Ten Commandments and similar statements of religious
20 doctrine;
21 b. The Christian cross, the Star of David, the Star and Crescent of
22 Islam, and similar symbols; and
23 c. Depictions of holy figures, prophets, or spiritual leaders for the
24 purpose of promoting religious adherence; and
25 2. Not including:
26 a. De minimis wardrobe items worn by others, including necklaces,
27 rings, or headdresses; and
Page 4 of 10
XXXX 2/23/2026 12:50 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2268
1 b. Displays in a private office area, so long as the display is not
2 obvious to students or the public;
3 (f) The right to be free from school-sponsored religious messaging on school
4 property or at school events, including at school assemblies and in the
5 classroom. This paragraph shall not prohibit:
6 1. Student-created religious expression in individual assignments or
7 projects, so long as the work addresses the learning objectives required
8 by the curriculum;
9 2. Reasonable accommodation of religious practices, including:
10 a. Reasonable scheduling accommodations for religious
11 observances;
12 b. Dietary accommodations consistent with religious requirements;
13 c. Styling of hair or personal grooming practices consistent with
14 religious or cultural practices;
15 d. Wearing of religious items, jewelry, and regalia, including
16 Indigenous traditional regalia and religious items; and
17 e. Any personal expression of religious practices, or of nonbelief,
18 provided it does not interfere with the rights of others or the safe
19 and normal functioning of the school, and provided it is not done
20 by school officials;
21 (g) The right to refuse to engage in religious discussions or otherwise reject
22 unwanted proselytizing by other students; and
23 (h) The right to be free from incentives, offered from either the school or a
24 school official, to participate in religious activities during school hours
25 facilitated by third-party organizations, including but not limited to offers of
26 money, food, school supplies, or other items not otherwise available in the
27 school.
