1 (3) No later than November 1, 2026, each school district shall establish a formal
2 grievance procedure for students, parents, and school officials to report violations
3 of this section. At a minimum, the grievance procedure shall require that:
4 (a) Within seven (7) days, complaints are acknowledged by the school district;
5 (b) Within fourteen (14) days, investigations of complaints are initiated by the
6 school district;
7 (c) Within forty (40) days or immediately upon completing the investigation
8 required by paragraph (b) of this subsection, whichever occurs first,
9 complaints are responded to with a written determination and an action
10 plan identifying necessary and specific steps to remediate any violations
11 found; and
12 (d) Complainants have a right to appeal to the local board of education.
13 (4) (a) Any student or parent of a student who alleges a violation of this section
14 that occurs on or after November 1, 2026, may bring a civil action in a court
15 of competent jurisdiction for declaratory, monetary, and injunctive relief
16 within two (2) years from the date of the alleged violation.
17 (b) For purposes of enforcing this section, any student currently enrolled or
18 who was enrolled in a public school at the time of the alleged violation, or
19 his or her parent or guardian, shall have standing to bring a civil action
20 under this subsection, without having to demonstrate an economic injury.
21 (c) Courts may award reasonable attorney's fees and costs to prevailing
22 plaintiffs, including plaintiffs awarded nominal damages and plaintiffs that
23 receive a preliminary injunction prior to a case being dismissed.
24 (d) Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, sovereign immunity
25 and governmental immunity are hereby waived for any claim alleging a
26 violation of this section.
27 (5) A school official shall not be subject to discipline or retaliation for reporting, in
Page 6 of 10
XXXX 2/23/2026 12:50 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2268
1 good faith, a violation of this section.
2 (6) (a) The Kentucky Department of Education shall:
3 1. By September 1, 2026, provide model policies and guidance documents
4 to assist local implementation of this section; and
5 2. By October 1, 2026, develop and provide training materials on
6 compliance with this section.
7 (b) Beginning with the 2026-2027 school year, school districts shall provide
8 training to all school officials on compliance with this section.
9 Section 2. KRS 158.175 is amended to read as follows:
10 (1) As a continuation of the policy of teaching our country's history[ and as an
11 affirmation of the freedom of religion in this country], the board of education of a
12 local school district may authorize the recitation of[ the traditional Lord's prayer
13 and] the pledge of allegiance to the flag in public elementary schools. Pupil
14 participation in the recitation of the[ prayer and] pledge of allegiance shall be
15 voluntary.[ Pupils shall be reminded that this Lord's prayer is the prayer our pilgrim
16 fathers recited when they came to this country in their search for freedom. Pupils
17 shall be informed that these exercises are not meant to influence an individual's
18 personal religious beliefs in any manner. The exercises shall be conducted so that
19 pupils shall learn of our great freedoms, including the freedom of religion
20 symbolized by the recitation of the Lord's prayer.]
21 (2) The board of education of each school district shall establish a policy and develop
22 procedures whereby the pupils in each elementary and secondary school may
23 participate in the pledge of allegiance to the flag of the United States at the
24 commencement of each school day.
25 (3) The Kentucky Board of Education shall develop a program of instruction relating to
26 the flag of the United States of America, including instruction in etiquette, the
27 correct use and display of the flag, and other patriotic exercises as may be related.
